diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.rationale: SLE can present with proteinuria due to kidney involvement, pericardial effusion, and acute pericarditis as manifestations of serositis, and dyspigmentation due to skin involvement.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.rationale: Though less common, rheumatoid arthritis can cause pericardial effusion and acute pericarditis; renal involvement might lead to proteinuria and skin manifestations can include dyspigmentation.

diagnoses.name: Scleroderma (Systemic Sclerosis)
diagnoses.rationale: Scleroderma can lead to dyspigmentation, pericardial effusion, and renal crisis (proteinuria). Pericarditis is less common but can occur.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.rationale: Dermatomyositis involves muscle and skin primarily but can have associated pericarditis and proteinuria due to renal involvement. Dyspigmentation can occur with the characteristic rash.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease (MCTD)
diagnoses.rationale: MCTD can present with symptoms that overlap those of SLE, scleroderma, and polymyositis, including skin changes (dyspigmentation), renal involvement (proteinuria), and pericarditis.

diagnoses.name: Infective Endocarditis
diagnoses.rationale: In a specific context, infective endocarditis can cause proteinuria due to renal involvement, acute pericarditis from direct or immune-mediated mechanisms, and Janeway lesions which can be perceived as dyspigmentation.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.rationale: HIV can cause proteinuria due to renal disease (e.g., HIV-associated nephropathy), pericardial effusion, secondary acute pericarditis, and dyspigmentation from various dermatological conditions.

diagnoses.name: Viral Pericarditis
diagnoses.rationale: Certain viral infections can cause acute pericarditis and pericardial effusion. Proteinuria can occur in the context of renal involvement. Dyspigmentation is not directly related but might appear as a non-specific viral rash.

diagnoses.name: Tuberculosis (TB)
diagnoses.rationale: TB can cause pericarditis and pericardial effusion (especially in the setting of extrapulmonary TB) and dyspigmentation due to cutaneous TB. Proteinuria may be seen with renal TB.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.rationale: Lyme disease, especially in later stages, can manifest with acute pericarditis, potential dyspigmentation (e.g., erythema migrans), and, rarely, proteinuria through glomerular damage.

diagnoses: Autoimmune Thyroiditis (such as Hashimoto's disease with extrathyroidal manifestations)

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can cause inflammation and pain in any part of the body. Central nervous system involvement can lead to psychosis, and it can also result in kidney damage (proteinuria) and joint inflammation (synovitis, arthropathy).

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: A chronic inflammatory disorder affecting many joints, including those in the hands and feet. In severe cases, it can affect skin, eyes, lungs, heart, and blood vessels, potentially leading to synovitis and arthropathy.

diagnoses.name: Psoriatic Arthritis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory arthritis associated with psoriasis, characterized by joint pain, stiffness, and swelling. It can also involve the skin, leading to conditions that might be confused with follicular hyperkeratosis.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that affects the glands that make moisture. It sometimes accompanies other immune system disorders such as rheumatoid arthritis and lupus. It can lead to joint pain and swelling (arthropathy).

diagnoses.name: Systemic Sclerosis (Scleroderma)
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease characterized by changes in the texture and appearance of the skin due to collagen accumulation. This disease can affect joints (arthropathy) and kidneys (proteinuria), and in rare cases, cause psychosis.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease marked by muscle weakness and skin rash. The rash could possibly mimic follicular hyperkeratosis. It is sometimes associated with other conditions that can lead to joint issues (arthropathy) and kidney involvement (proteinuria).

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder that may include features of lupus, scleroderma, and polymyositis. Patients may experience a wide range of symptoms including joint pain (arthropathy), kidney involvement (proteinuria), and skin issues.

diagnoses.name: Henoch-Schönlein Purpura
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of blood vessels (vasculitis) that can affect the kidneys (leading to proteinuria), joints (arthropathy), and skin. Although not commonly associated with psychosis, systemic inflammation can have diverse effects.

diagnoses.name: Polyarteritis Nodosa
diagnoses.description: A serious blood vessel disease where small and medium-sized arteries become swollen and damaged. It can affect any organ, including the kidneys (proteinuria), joints (arthropathy), and potentially affect mental status.

diagnoses.name: Lupus Nephritis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the kidneys caused by systemic lupus erythematosus. It is a specific type of kidney inflammation that is directly caused by lupus, leading to proteinuria, and is associated with arthropathy.

diagnoses.description: Hypertension
diagnoses.detail: High blood pressure can lead to damage of the blood vessels, causing Polycythemia, dyslipidemia, and could indirectly affect vision and cognitive functions.

diagnoses.description: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.detail: High blood sugar levels can lead to difficulty focusing vision, contribute to dyslipidemia, Polycythemia through alterations in blood viscosity, and affect cognitive functions like word finding.

diagnoses.description: Polycythemia Vera
diagnoses.detail: A type of blood cancer that leads to an abnormal increase in blood cells (Polycythemia), which could indirectly affect vision, cognitive function, and could be associated with skin rashes.

diagnoses.description: Hyperlipidemia
diagnoses.detail: An elevation of lipids in the bloodstream, directly responsible for dyslipidemia, and can contribute to systemic conditions impacting vision, cognitive functions, and skin health.

diagnoses.description: Thyroid Disorders
diagnoses.detail: Conditions such as hypothyroidism or hyperthyroidism can lead to dyslipidemia, cognitive dysfunctions like word-finding difficulty, and can affect the skin causing rashes.

diagnoses.description: Vitamin B12 Deficiency
diagnoses.detail: Deficiency can cause cognitive problems, including word-finding difficulty, and may also affect vision. Polycythemia may occur as a secondary condition.

diagnoses.description: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.detail: An autoimmune disease that can cause widespread symptoms including rashes, Polycythemia, and cognitive issues, potentially affecting vision and lipid metabolism.

diagnoses.description: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.detail: A disease affecting the brain and spinal cord can lead to vision problems, cognitive challenges like word-finding difficulty, and indirectly affect skin health.

diagnoses.description: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.detail: An autoimmune disease that primarily affects joints but can have systemic effects such as dyslipidemia, and skin rashes, and potentially influence cognitive function.

diagnoses.description: Chronic Kidney Disease
diagnoses.detail: Impaired kidney function can lead to a build-up of toxins which may cause a range of symptoms including dyslipidemia, Polycythemia, cognitive issues, and skin rashes.

diagnoses.name: Hemophagocytic Lymphohistiocytosis
diagnoses.description: A rare but potentially fatal disorder caused by excessive activation of macrophages and lymphocytes, leading to severe hyperinflammation.

diagnoses.name: Adult Still's Disease
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disorder that leads to fever, joint pain, and a distinctive salmon-colored rash, often associated with high levels of ferritin.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can affect any part of the body, leading to widespread inflammation and tissue damage in the affected organs.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: A chronic inflammatory disorder affecting many joints, including those in the hands and feet, leading to painful swelling and potential joint deformity.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease that affects multiple organs in the body, but mostly the lungs and lymph glands, characterized by the formation of granulomas.

diagnoses.name: Infectious Mononucleosis
diagnoses.description: An infection usually caused by the Epstein-Barr virus (EBV) that leads to fever, sore throat, swollen lymph glands, and fatigue.

diagnoses.name: Lymphoma
diagnoses.description: A group of blood cancers that develop from lymphocytes, marked by lymphadenopathy, fever, night sweats, and weight loss.

diagnoses.name: Behcet's Disease
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder causing blood vessel inflammation throughout your body, leading to various symptoms including mouth and genital ulcers, and eye inflammation.

diagnoses.name: Tuberculosis
diagnoses.description: A bacterial infection caused by Mycobacterium tuberculosis, which most often affects the lungs but can also affect other parts of the body.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.description: Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) is a virus that attacks the immune system. If not treated, it can lead to the disease AIDS (acquired immunodeficiency syndrome).

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid arthritis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder that primarily affects joints, leading to pain, swelling, and potential loss of function. It can also cause dryness and irritation in the eyes.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder characterized by dry eyes and mouth, joint pain, and sometimes abnormalities in the blood, including electrolyte imbalances.

diagnoses.name: Lupus
diagnoses.description: A systemic autoimmune disease that can affect many parts of the body, including the joints, skin, kidneys, blood cells, brain, heart, and lungs. Symptoms can include joint pain, skin rashes, and renal issues leading to abnormal electrolyte levels.

diagnoses.name: Graft-versus-host disease (GVHD)
diagnoses.description: A complication that can occur after a bone marrow or stem cell transplant in which the donated bone marrow or peripheral blood stem cells view the recipient's body as foreign and attack the body. This can lead to symptoms such as dry or irritated eyes, joint pain, and electrolyte imbalances.

diagnoses.name: Chronic myeloid leukemia (CML)
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer that starts in certain blood-forming cells of the bone marrow. It can lead to an increased level of basophils and other white blood cells. Symptoms may include fatigue, night sweats, and joint pain.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease that affects multiple organs in the body, but mostly the lungs and lymph glands. It can cause joint pain and eye irritation, with possible electrolyte imbalance due to kidney involvement.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which your thyroid gland doesn't produce enough thyroid hormones. It can lead to joint pain, dryness or irritation of the eyes, and abnormal electrolyte levels.

diagnoses.name: Polychondritis
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder characterized by inflammation of cartilage and other tissues throughout the body. Symptoms can include joint pain, red and painful eyes, and potentially abnormal electrolyte levels due to systemic inflammation.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes mellitus
diagnoses.description: A group of diseases that affect how your body uses blood sugar (glucose). While not directly causing dysgeusia or basophilia, it can lead to joint pain, eye issues (including irritation), and electrolyte imbalances, especially in poorly controlled diabetes.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.description: Human immunodeficiency virus/acquired immunodeficiency syndrome can lead to a wide variety of symptoms, including joint pain, eye irritation, and electrolyte imbalances due to renal involvement or the effects of the virus itself on the body.
